## What All Inclusive Actually Covers in Colorado Ski Packages

When resorts say "all inclusive," they typically mean lodging, some meals, and lift tickets. What they don't include creates a web of additional costs and logistical problems that can easily double your expected budget.

Most packages include breakfast and dinner but not lunch on the mountain, which runs $25-35 per person at base lodge cafeterias. Ski rentals get included at basic levels, but if you need performance skis, boots that actually fit properly, or any equipment beyond standard recreational gear, you're looking at $40-60 per day in upgrade fees. Ski lessons often get bundled, but only group lessons with 8-12 other skiers. Private instruction costs an additional $150-200 per hour.

Transportation represents the biggest gap. I've seen families arrive at Denver International Airport expecting shuttle service to their resort, only to discover their "comprehensive" package requires them to arrange their own ground transportation. **[Car service from Denver airport](https://expresscoloradotransportation.com/car-service-denver-airport/)** to places like Vail or Aspen can cost $300-500 one way, especially during peak season when demand spikes and weather creates delays.

